course_title: SELECTED TOPICS IN MGMT: Labour Relations in Professional Sports
subject: COM

sections.description: This course will examine labour relations and collective bargaining in North American professional sports with a particular emphasis on the major sports leagues.  Particular topics will include issues as strikes and lockouts, drug testing, free agency, the role of agents and health and safety issues in professional sports.  Course components will include a collective bargaining simulation and a grievance arbitration exercise.  Subject to availability, there will also be some guest speakers.

course_title: SELECTED TOPICS IN MGMT: Social Entrepreneurship
subject: COM

sections.description:
Contemporary democratic societies are built around three sectors – government, business and civil society (also known as the non-profit sector). In order to drive societies towards a state of equilibrium, these three sectors should function together efficiently. However, in recent years the boundaries between these sectors has begun to blur with the emergence of social enterprises. Social entrepreneurship refers to innovative, social value creating activity that can occur within or across the government, business or civil society sectors. Social enterprise organizations – both those operating as for profit and non-profit entities – require the appropriate skills in order to address new and complex societal challenges while also maintaining the economic viability of their organizational forms.

The main goal of the course is to explore the importance of social entrepreneurship and social intrapreneurship that helps find solutions to the major challenges facing today’s societies and to foster a positive disposition towards becoming personally involved in some way in a social enterprise initiative in the future. The course examines the nature of social entrepreneurship and the major trends affecting the field of social enterprise. It will encompass aspects of strategy, governance, accountability, leadership, fund-raising, scaling up and social impact that social entrepreneurs and intrapreneurs should be aware of.
